WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.333
How many Americans
do you think live in a wildfire risk zone?

00:00:04.333 --> 00:00:05.083
The answer?

00:00:05.083 --> 00:00:07.625
A third of the U.S. population.

00:00:07.625 --> 00:00:09.750
This number used to be 1 in 6.

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:12.000
And fire season is only growing.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.041
Now to the dry and hot conditions
fueling dozens of wildfires in the West.

00:00:16.083 --> 00:00:19.916
This fire burning so hot it's
creating its own erratic weather system.

00:00:20.125 --> 00:00:23.541
This fire, just one of hundreds
burning across North America right now.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
On average, a whole month has been added
to fire season

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:28.916
in parts of the Western U.S.

00:00:28.916 --> 00:00:30.083
It starts earlier.

00:00:30.083 --> 00:00:30.958
It goes longer.

00:00:30.958 --> 00:00:33.083
We can have fires any time of the year.

00:00:33.083 --> 00:00:35.916
Fire season is now fire year.

00:00:35.916 --> 00:00:38.416
Right now, across the American West,
as we're entering

00:00:38.416 --> 00:00:41.250
some of the worst fire conditions
we've ever faced this season,

00:00:41.250 --> 00:00:43.833
we also have some of the lowest staffing
that we've ever had

00:00:43.833 --> 00:00:45.125
for a wildland firefighters.

00:00:45.125 --> 00:00:47.000
That's a recipe for disaster.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:47.666
And while the

00:00:47.666 --> 00:00:51.583
government does share some wildfire data,
it doesn't always tell the story

00:00:51.583 --> 00:00:52.333
on the ground.

00:00:52.333 --> 00:00:54.083
Specifically, around the health

00:00:54.083 --> 00:00:57.583
and well-being of those protecting
the most rural parts of America:

00:00:57.583 --> 00:00:59.750
the wildland firefighters.

00:00:59.873 --> 00:01:02.541
Working 16 hour days in extreme heat.

00:01:02.791 --> 00:01:04.041
Sleeping in smoke.

00:01:04.041 --> 00:01:06.625
Breathing smoke.
That takes a toll on your body.

00:01:06.625 --> 00:01:08.458
So what does it take for wildland

00:01:08.458 --> 00:01:12.083
firefighters to battle
these increasingly intense fires?

00:01:12.416 --> 00:01:16.041
And how can communities across
rural America protect themselves?

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:18.750
We're seeing the greatest

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:23.125
relative increase in acres
burned above elevations at 8000ft.

00:01:23.125 --> 00:01:24.833
If you are a firefighter in the 90s,

00:01:24.833 --> 00:01:27.500
you might say,
oh, you know that area can't burn.

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:30.500
And now we're seeing those areas
burn really vigorously.

00:01:30.833 --> 00:01:31.666
Climate change,

00:01:31.666 --> 00:01:35.708
which is driving higher temperatures
and drier conditions, is one component.

00:01:36.083 --> 00:01:38.291
The human factor is another.

00:01:38.291 --> 00:01:41.333
85% of wildfires are started by humans.

00:01:41.666 --> 00:01:43.916
So where humans live and recreate.

00:01:43.916 --> 00:01:46.916
Like hiking, camping and traveling.
Matter.

00:01:47.125 --> 00:01:49.750
People are moving outside of urban centers

00:01:49.750 --> 00:01:53.958
more into the hazardous
wildfire prone areas.

00:01:54.041 --> 00:01:57.083
But when I started fighting fires
in the 70s,

00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:01.625
there weren't that many rural subdivisions
in the woods.

00:02:01.666 --> 00:02:02.625
Bobby is referring

00:02:02.625 --> 00:02:07.041
to the expansion of what is known
as the wildland urban Interface or WUI.

00:02:07.375 --> 00:02:11.208
The WUI is the zone of transition
where houses and buildings are built close

00:02:11.208 --> 00:02:16.375
to unoccupied wildland areas,
creating zones of high wildfire risk.

00:02:17.125 --> 00:02:20.125
You've really exacerbated the problem
because you put all this

00:02:20.125 --> 00:02:25.500
flammable material in and all these points
of ignitions with these homes.

00:02:25.791 --> 00:02:28.958
But do people know the actual risks
of living in the WUI?

00:02:29.375 --> 00:02:33.375
People aren't very concerned
because they think the fire department

00:02:33.375 --> 00:02:34.375
is going to come save them.

00:02:34.375 --> 00:02:39.291
But when the weather and climate and 
fuel and everything goes against them,

00:02:39.291 --> 00:02:42.083
there's not much anybody's
going to do against a large fire.

00:02:42.083 --> 00:02:47.458
So the biggest thing is getting people
to understand the stresses

00:02:47.458 --> 00:02:52.250
on a traditional seasonal fire
service has grown immensely.

00:02:52.541 --> 00:02:56.125
The time away from home,
the amount of work that you have to do,

00:02:56.375 --> 00:03:00.958
the duration, the smoke accumulation
that firefighters go through.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.375
We're having a lot more wildland fires
that become wildland urban interface

00:03:05.375 --> 00:03:06.041
fires.

00:03:06.041 --> 00:03:08.708
People are realizing that,
hey, I'm breathing this smoke.

00:03:08.708 --> 00:03:11.791
You know, 100 homes on fire, you know,

00:03:11.791 --> 00:03:15.583
with their plastics and their thousands
of different chemical compounds.

00:03:15.958 --> 00:03:20.666
Wildland firefighters are exposed to 31
carcinogens in the line of duty.

00:03:20.875 --> 00:03:24.791
It's extremely difficult to staff
crews of wildland firefighters now

00:03:25.208 --> 00:03:28.541
because the difficulty of the conditions
they're facing has outpaced

00:03:28.541 --> 00:03:29.750
their compensation.

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:31.666
What does it take to support them?

00:03:31.666 --> 00:03:35.250
It takes healthcare so that the people
with the expertise to manage

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:38.250
these fires will keep working
and stay healthy doing so.

00:03:38.375 --> 00:03:39.625
Protecting and properly

00:03:39.625 --> 00:03:43.583
compensating wildland firefighters
is a critical piece of the equation.

00:03:43.625 --> 00:03:46.208
But there's also education and awareness,

00:03:46.208 --> 00:03:48.875
which we'll get back to
right after this message.

00:03:48.875 --> 00:03:50.041
This is another episode

00:03:50.041 --> 00:03:54.208
in a series of videos we're doing on
how emergency help gets to remote places.

00:03:54.208 --> 00:03:55.375
Rural parts of the U.S.

00:03:55.375 --> 00:03:58.708
often struggle to get the same services
as more populated regions.

00:03:58.750 --> 00:04:00.958
We wanted to explore
what those challenges look like

00:04:00.958 --> 00:04:02.833
and what might be done
to make things better.

