00:04:21.125 --> 00:04:22.583
Now back to the video.

00:04:22.583 --> 00:04:23.541
We're trying to help

00:04:23.541 --> 00:04:27.500
everyone understand you can do things
around your own property.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.541
Sometimes it's firescaping.

00:04:29.541 --> 00:04:32.333
Lois is referring
to fire adapted communities,

00:04:32.333 --> 00:04:36.000
a framework for educating communities
to be fire resilient.

00:04:36.583 --> 00:04:37.958
Start right around your home.

00:04:37.958 --> 00:04:39.583
Do the 0 to 5ft zone.

00:04:39.583 --> 00:04:42.000
Make sure that that's as safe
as it can be.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.041
These zones refer to defensive buffers
between houses

00:04:45.041 --> 00:04:48.041
and wildfires.
And the first zone of defense:

00:04:48.291 --> 00:04:51.000
Homeowners should clear their gutters
and remove firewood,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.916
debris, and other flammable materials.
In the second zone,

00:04:55.208 --> 00:04:56.666
they should design landscaping

00:04:56.666 --> 00:05:00.166
to create breaks
with smaller clusters of trees and shrubs.

00:05:00.833 --> 00:05:03.333
Bob Roper and his colleagues
have also developed

00:05:03.333 --> 00:05:08.208
a program called ready, set, go to help
fire departments and vulnerable residents

00:05:08.208 --> 00:05:11.333
learn what to do before, during
and after a fire.

00:05:11.875 --> 00:05:15.416
And I think the public should,
you know, really think about the future.

00:05:15.416 --> 00:05:19.583
Think about how they want to be protected
by the fire service, by contextualizing

00:05:19.583 --> 00:05:22.666
the fact that, you know,
we haven't seen the worst fire

00:05:22.708 --> 00:05:27.208
we're going to continue to see ever
increasing larger fires, more destructive.

00:05:27.666 --> 00:05:31.250
I think it's more important than ever
for people

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:35.125
to think about fire,
not as a singular thing, but fire plural.

00:05:35.625 --> 00:05:38.875
The most resilient tool
we have to fight fires in the U.S.

00:05:38.875 --> 00:05:42.750
utilizes indigenous fire
practices of controlled burns.

00:05:42.833 --> 00:05:46.333
There are also kinds of fire
that a lot of our ecosystems

00:05:46.333 --> 00:05:50.791
in California, but all across North
America evolved to thrive with.

00:05:51.083 --> 00:05:53.500
And if we can bring back
the good kinds of fire,

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:56.541
the kinds of fires that these ecosystems
need,

00:05:56.916 --> 00:05:59.791
then we can really make our landscapes
more resilient.

00:05:59.791 --> 00:06:02.875
We can do the fuel mitigation,
we can remove the fuel.

00:06:02.875 --> 00:06:07.041
But the research shows that prescribed
fire really has to happen.

00:06:07.166 --> 00:06:09.208
While
the state of California has partnered

00:06:09.208 --> 00:06:12.708
with the Karuk in Klamath Tribes
to practice controlled burns,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.583
it's only one small step
to fighting these growing fires.

00:06:16.875 --> 00:06:20.666
Addressing climate change,
encouraging fire, safe rural planning

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.583
and increasing support for wildland
firefighters will be just as critical.

00:06:29.875 --> 00:06:30.375
For.

